The dataset is basically the data provided for the first 3 months of the year 2022,it contains a combined total of 529086 rides

GATHERING DATA¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made using Baywheels in San Fransisco in the first 3 months of 2022. this data was downloaded from https://s3.amazonaws.com/baywheels-data/index.html and multiple data files needed to be joined together to get a single dataset that requires some wrangling to make the data neat enough for analysis.

Getting 2022(first 3 months) Baywheels data zip file¶

In [2]:
# defining a function to get the csv file
def get_file(month,year=2022):
    r=re.get(f'https://s3.amazonaws.com/baywheels-data/{year}{month}-baywheels-tripdata.csv.zip')
    z = zipfile.ZipFile(io.BytesIO(r.content))
    csv=z.open(f'{year}{month}-baywheels-tripdata.csv')
    
    df=pd.read_csv(csv)
    df.to_csv(f'Baywheels{month}-{year}.csv',index = False)

OBSERVATIONS¶

  • TIDINESS
    • The df1,df2,df3 datasets column can be further simplified by intorducing new columns
    • Melt the 3 dataframes together
    • Some of the df1,df2,df3 dataset columns can also be dropped
    • Rename some columns
  • QUALITY
    • The datatype of some of the columns can be modified
    • Some rows start location and end location are the same giving a wrong start and end time
    • The time can be calculated using the respective start and end date

CREATION OF NEW COLUMNS¶

Obtaining the time duration of each ride¶

Define¶

Using the start and end date to get the time duration then converting it to get the duration in minutes,hours and days

Code¶

In [28]:
# Converting the started at and ended at columns to datetime datatype
df_2022['started_at'] = pd.to_datetime(df_2022['started_at'])
df_2022['ended_at'] =  pd.to_datetime(df_2022['ended_at'])
(df_2022.ended_at - df_2022.started_at).dt.total_seconds()



# get the seconds for hours + minutes + seconds, but not days
# note the difference from total_seconds
df_2022.insert(1,'duration_in_seconds',(df_2022.ended_at - df_2022.started_at).dt.seconds)
df_2022.insert(2,'duration_in_minutes',df_2022.duration_in_seconds/60)
df_2022.insert(3,'duration_in_hours',df_2022.duration_in_seconds/3600)

THE START LOCATION AND END LOCATION ARE THE SAME GIVING UNREALISTIC TIME DURATIONS¶

Define¶

Unrealistic time durations need to be removed e.g 0 seconds,1 second

Code¶

In [30]:
# The duration of some rides is 0 and 1 second which isnt realistic
df_2022 = df_2022[df_2022['start_station_name'] != df_2022['end_station_name']] 
df_2022['start_lat'] = df_2022['start_lat'].round(2)    
df_2022['end_lat'] = df_2022['end_lat'].round(2) 
df_2022 = df_2022[df_2022['start_lat'] != df_2022['end_lat']]
df_2022= df_2022.drop(105118)

Conclusions¶

The insights that stood out were;

  • No member made use of the docked bike and there was a general preference for the electric bike
  • March was the best month among the first 3 months of 2022 for the Baywheels bike sharing system and there was a gradual increase in the number of rides across the first 3 months hinting at increasing popularity 
     -   The key insights answer the following questions;
    • Which bike should be purchased if the Baywheels bike sharing system wants to expand its current capacity?
    • Is the method at which services is being carried out working? The Baywheels bike sharing system dataset was a very insightful one and the insights obtained will surely help the business make well informed decisions.
